{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01PZjov1qoNtXRHUypThnM8Z","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I understand the architecture. The request wrapper classes like `NewUserRequestWrapper` have a `user` field — the JSON is `{\"user\": {\"username\":...}}`. The wrapper already handles the nesting without `@JsonRootName`. But with `UNWRAP_ROOT_VALUE` enabled as the primary ObjectMapper, Spring's `HttpMessageConverter` would try to unwrap a root, looking for a `@JsonRootName` annotation on `NewUserRequestWrapper` — which doesn't have one. This would cause deserialization failures.\n\nThe core issue is: **the wrapping ObjectMapper should NOT be the primary one used by Spring MVC's message converters**. It should only be used for manual serialization in the controllers. The default Spring MVC ObjectMapper should be the non-wrapping one.\n\nLet me also check if there's a 403 issue specifically — let me look at the container logs:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1859,"cache_read_input_tokens":48414,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1859,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":295},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d8d75e0c-f395-45d5-b7d7-3f60b39c8ca5","uuid":"757b239c-0dc8-4107-b88a-71843234cc80"}
