{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01DBRwdqnTy24KKkD1kSY338","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I need to fix how the controllers and resources handle the wrapping ObjectMapper for deserialization too. Since the primary ObjectMapper is now the non-wrapping one, Spring MVC will deserialize `{\"user\": {\"username\":...}}` normally — the wrapper classes (`NewUserRequestWrapper`, `LoginRequestWrapper`, etc.) already have a `user` field, so they'll deserialize correctly without root unwrapping.\n\nFor serialization, the controllers that manually use `objectMapper.writeValueAsString()` with the wrapping ObjectMapper will continue to work correctly — `UserResponse` has `@JsonRootName(\"user\")`, `ArticleResponse` has `@JsonRootName(\"article\")`, etc.\n\nNow let me fix the TagsResource — it currently returns `ResponseEntity<TagsResponse>` directly, which means Spring MVC will serialize it with the primary (non-wrapping) ObjectMapper, giving `{\"tags\": []}` — which is actually correct now! The non-wrapping ObjectMapper won't add the extra `TagsResponse` wrapper.\n\nWait — but TagsResource returns `ResponseEntity<TagsResponse>` directly through Spring's message converter, not through manual `objectMapper.writeValueAsString()`. With the non-wrapping ObjectMapper as primary, this will now correctly produce `{\"tags\": []}`.\n\nNow let me also check if there's a 403 issue. Looking at the logs again, the error was `HttpMessageNotReadableException` (400) not 403. Let me re-check:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":551,"cache_read_input_tokens":54000,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":551,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":478},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d8d75e0c-f395-45d5-b7d7-3f60b39c8ca5","uuid":"16c5cd48-9746-4c6c-8714-4e7feb110f24"}
