{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01KkJm2uhaa5frDDeCFSM6UE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"It is indeed returning 403. But the security config has `requestMatchers(HttpMethod.POST, \"/api/users\", \"/api/users/login\").permitAll()`. The issue is likely that after the deserialization error (HttpMessageNotReadableException), Spring Security's error handling catches it and returns 403 because the error dispatch path isn't permitted. Or it could be that Spring Security is denying the request before it even reaches the controller.\n\nWait - looking more carefully, the first smoke test call to `/api/tags` returns 200 fine, and the POST to `/api/users` returns 403 with empty body. This could be because the request is rejected by Spring Security before even reaching the controller. Let me check if Spring Security's `permitAll()` patterns are matching correctly.\n\nActually, looking at the log output, the `HttpMessageNotReadableException` error from earlier smoke tests happened on a different request. The 403 on the POST might be because of the way the path is being matched. Let me look at this more carefully.\n\nThe issue might be that Spring Security's `requestMatchers` with `HttpMethod.POST, \"/api/users\"` works differently from what we expect. With Spring Boot 3.x, the default path matching may not match POST to `/api/users` correctly. But also, the `permitAll()` should still allow the request through since `anyRequest().authenticated()` shouldn't prevent it.\n\nWait — actually this is a known Spring Security behavior. When `anyRequest().authenticated()` is set and there's an error during request handling (like deserialization), Spring Security intercepts the error dispatch and returns 403 because the error page isn't permitted. But actually, the 403 is happening even before the request body is read.\n\nLet me check if there might be an issue with the `/api/users` path — the CORS configuration is registered on `/api/**` which should match. Let me look at the Spring Security debug:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1089,"cache_read_input_tokens":54551,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1089,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":563},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d8d75e0c-f395-45d5-b7d7-3f60b39c8ca5","uuid":"662b30d6-392e-4471-a252-3a1c06415c7d"}
