{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_017yeEjCBUQFASgnTy3njRJS","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.example.realworldapi.application.web.model.response;\n     2→\n     3→import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonRootName;\n     4→import lombok.Getter;\n     5→import lombok.Setter;\n     6→\n     7→import java.util.LinkedList;\n     8→import java.util.List;\n     9→\n    10→@Getter\n    11→@Setter\n    12→@JsonRootName(\"errors\")\n    13→public class ErrorResponse {\n    14→\n    15→    private List<String> body;\n    16→\n    17→    public ErrorResponse() {\n    18→        this.body = new LinkedList<>();\n    19→    }\n    20→\n    21→    public ErrorResponse(String error) {\n    22→        this();\n    23→        this.body.add(error);\n    24→    }\n    25→\n    26→    public ErrorResponse(List<String> errors) {\n    27→        this.body = errors;\n    28→    }\n    29→}\n    30→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d8d75e0c-f395-45d5-b7d7-3f60b39c8ca5","uuid":"f8510114-0607-41c8-9391-0d85f51d9ac0"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01HBzWErc3B5BYam3eJv6AGH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ErrorResponse has `@JsonRootName(\"errors\")` and is serialized using the wrapping ObjectMapper in GlobalExceptionHandler. That's correct.\n\nNow, the key issue with the GlobalExceptionHandler: it uses the wrapping ObjectMapper (`@Qualifier(\"wrappingObjectMapper\")`), which will still produce correct wrapped output like `{\"errors\": {\"body\": [...]}}`. That's fine.\n\nBut there's also the issue that the GlobalExceptionHandler uses `ResponseEntity<String>` — it manually serializes. So the wrapping ObjectMapper there is fine.\n\nNow let me also check how the `@RequestBody` deserialization works for request wrappers. Since the primary ObjectMapper is now the non-wrapping one, Spring MVC will deserialize `{\"user\": {...}}` into `NewUserRequestWrapper` which has a `user` field — this should work correctly.\n\nLet me now rebuild and test. Let me stop the old container, rebuild, and start fresh:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":599,"cache_read_input_tokens":67020,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":599,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":826},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d8d75e0c-f395-45d5-b7d7-3f60b39c8ca5","uuid":"6bf2cd99-6329-4dda-abbf-e9c3463289ec"}
